# Security Rules

- Treat all user input as untrusted.
- Validate and sanitize all incoming data.
- Never expose sensitive internal information.

# Authentication

- Use secure authentication practices.
- Never store plaintext secrets.
- Use environment variables for sensitive configuration.
- Protect routes properly.

# Authorization

- Always verify ownership and permissions.
- Never rely on frontend authorization.
- Use policies and gates consistently.

# Database Security

- Use parameterized queries only.
- Prevent mass assignment vulnerabilities.
- Protect transactional consistency.

# Auction Security

- Prevent race conditions during bidding.
- Use transactions for all bid operations.
- Ensure bids cannot bypass minimum increments.
- Prevent bidding after auction expiration.

# File Uploads

- Validate file types and sizes.
- Never trust uploaded file extensions.
- Store uploads securely.

# API Security

- Rate limit sensitive endpoints.
- Avoid leaking stack traces.
- Return safe error messages.

# Realtime Security

- Authenticate websocket connections.
- Prevent unauthorized event subscriptions.
- Avoid broadcasting sensitive data.

# Logging

- Never log secrets or passwords.
- Log security-relevant events appropriately.

# Dependencies

- Avoid unnecessary packages.
- Prefer mature and maintained libraries.
- Watch for vulnerable dependencies.